Human Rights, Zakiya Luna highlights the often-forgotten activism of women of color who are largely responsible for creating what we now know as the modern-day reproductive justice movement.Focusing on SisterSong, an intersectional reproductive justice organization, Luna shows how, and why, women of color mobilized around reproductive rights in the domestic arena. She examines their key role in re-framing reproductive rights as human rights, raising this set of issues as a priority in the United States, a country hostile to the concept of human rights at home.An indispensable read, Reproductive Rights as Human Rights provides a much-needed intersectional perspective on the modern-day reproductive justice movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aBirth controlzUnited States. 0aHuman rightszUnited States. 0aMinority womenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen's rightszUnited States. 0aWomen, BlackzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  a1996 welfare reform.  aAfrican Americans.  aBeijing.  aBlack Women’s Health Project.  aBlack feminism.  aBlack feminists.  aConvention on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW).  aFord Foundation.  aHyde Amendment.  aNational Organization for Women.  aNative American.  aNew Voices.  aPuerto Rico.  aRJ 101.  aRoe v. Wade.  aStupak-Pitts Amendment.  aSupreme Court.  aUnited Nations (UN).  aUniversal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR).  aUniversal Periodic Review (UPR).  aWomen’s Marches.  aWorld Conference on Women.  aabortion.  aadvocacy.  acivil rights.  acoalition.  adefining human rights.  adomestic jurisdiction.  adomestication.  aeconomic rights.  aeducation.  aenterprise.  aenvisionin